<div class="postright">
<h3>Insane trouble with realtek wifi card</h3>
<div class="postmsg">
<p>I&#039;ve searched to no end and tried a pile of different solutions, but I can&#039;t seem to get my realtek wifi card to work properly on ANY linux distribution i&#039;ve tried. Parrot is my favorite distro by a mile mind and also seems to have the newest kernel that I&#039;ve seen in a released distro (at least one that uses dpkg, but pacman / rpm isn&#039;t an option for me) so seems to be the best place to work from. </p><p>The default firmware-realtek package that parrot provides offers dismal performance and the connection seems to drop after about 5 minutes or so despite the connection icon remaining. I&#039;ve downloaded the latest drivers and installed them manually (after removing firmware-realtek) but it seems to be even worse (or maybe just more accurate?). With those drivers the connection alternates between fast / slow for about 2 minutes then the wifi icon will drop to connecting and never move past until a reboot, in which the cycle continues. </p><p>From what I&#039;ve read I&#039;m not the only one with these kinds of problems with realtek cards and linux, I&#039;m curious if anyone has any input / solutions / experience or am I gonna have to swap out my card in order to get this working? It&#039;d be a shame to do so, as this is otherwise a great laptop but windows is simply not an option for me.&#160; </p><p>On a default installation of regular ol&#039; debian, the installer asks for the following firmware files (which I tried installing manually, but it didn&#039;t help the aforementioned symptoms) </p><p>rtlwifi/rtl8821aefw.bin<br/>rtlwifi/rtl8821aefw_wowlan.bin</p><p>rtl_nic/rtl8168g-3.fw</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
